kernel_variant.question:
Let k \geq  1 be an integer and let  

  f : \mathbb{R}^k \longrightarrow  \mathbb{R}  

be defined on an open neighbourhood of the origin.  
Assume that f is twice Frechet-differentiable at 0; i.e. there exist  

 a linear map A : \mathbb{R}^k \longrightarrow  \mathbb{R}   and a symmetric bilinear form B : \mathbb{R}^k \times  \mathbb{R}^k \longrightarrow  \mathbb{R}  

such that  

  lim_{h\to 0}  [ f(h) - f(0) - A(h) - \frac{1}{2} B(h,h) ] / \|h\|^2 = 0. (\star )

For two sequences {a_n}, {b_n} \subset  \mathbb{R}^k suppose  

(i) a_n \neq  0, b_n \neq  0 for every n;  
(ii) a_n \to  0 and b_n \to  0;  
(iii) r_n := \|b_n - a_n\| \longrightarrow  0;  
(iv) u_n := (b_n - a_n) / r_n \longrightarrow  u  with \|u\| = 1;  
(v) m_n := (a_n + b_n)/2 satisfies \|m_n\| = o(r_n)  (the midpoint approaches 0 much faster than the chord-length).

Show that  

  lim_{n\to \infty } 4 \cdot  [ f(b_n) - 2 f(m_n) + f(a_n) ] / r_n^2 = B(u,u). (1)

In words: after the appropriate normalisation by the factor 4, the discrete second difference of f along any shrinking chord whose midpoint collapses sufficiently fast to the base point reproduces the quadratic form determined by the Hessian at 0.

